Nnedi Okorafor is an award-winning novelist of African-based science fiction, fantasy and magical realism. Born in the US to Nigerian immigrant parents, Okorafor is known for weaving African cultures into creative settings and memorable characters. Her books include Lagoon (a British Science Fiction Association Award finalist for best novel), Who Fears Death (a World Fantasy Award winner for best novel), Kabu Kabu (a Publisher's Weekly best book for Fall 2013), Akata Witch (an Amazon.com best book of the year), Zahrah the Windseeker (winner of the Wole Soyinka Prize for African Literature) and The Shadow Speaker (a CBS Parallax Award winner).

Her 2016 novel The Book of Phoenix is an Arthur C. Clarke Award finalist, while the first book in the Binti Trilogy won both the Hugo and Nebula Awards for Best Novella. Her children’s book Chicken in the Kitchen won an Africana Book Award. The final installment of the Binti Trilogy, titled The Night Masquerade, will be released in September 2017, and the sequel to Akata Witch (titled Akata Warrior) is was published in October 2017. Meanwhile, her book Who Fears Death has been optioned by HBO, with Game of Thrones' George R.R. Martin as executive producer.

Okorafor is a full professor at the University at Buffalo, New York (SUNY).

aws-transcripts.transcript: What if a African girl from a traditional family in a part of future Africa is accepted into the finest university in the galaxy, planets away? What if she decides to go? This is an excerpt from my Benty novella trilogy. I powered up the transporter and said a silent prayer. I had no idea what I was going to do if it didn't work. My transporter was cheap, so even the droplet of moisture or more likely, a grain of sand would cause it to short. It was faulty, and most of the time I had to restart it over and over before it worked. Please, not now, Please. Not now, I thought. The transporter shivered in the sand and I held my breath. Tiny flat and black is a prayer stone. It buzz softly and then slowly rose from the sand. Finally, it produced the baggage lifting force. I grinned. Now I could make it to the shuttle on time. I swiped the jet, say from my forehead with my index finger and melt down. Then I touched the finger to the sand, grounding the sweet smelling red clay into it. Thank you, I whispered. It was 1/2 mile walk along the dark doesn't road. With the transporter working, I would make it there on time, straightening up by pause and shut my eyes. Now the weight of my entire life was pressing on my shoulders. I was defying the most traditional part of myself. For the first time in my entire life.
